The term '''red-green-brown alliance''', originating in [[France]], refers to the alleged alliance of [[Left-wing politics|Leftists]] (''red''), ecologically-minded agrarians (''green''), and [[Islamism|Islamists]] (''brown'').<ref name="Judaken 2013 p. 197">{{cite book | last=Judaken | first=J. | title=Naming Race, Naming Racisms | publisher=Taylor & Francis | year=2013 | isbn=978-1-317-99156-4 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=haraAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA197 | page=197}}</ref><ref name="Sedgwick 2004 p. 258">{{cite book | last=Sedgwick | first=M. | title=Against the Modern World: Traditionalism and the Secret Intellectual History of the Twentieth Century | publisher=Oxford University Press | year=2004 | isbn=978-0-19-974493-0 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GcUFmQ-NF_0C&pg=PA258 | page=258f}}</ref><ref name="Flood Hutchings Miazhevich Nickels 2012 p. 137">{{cite book | last=Flood | first=C. | last2=Hutchings | first2=S. | last3=Miazhevich | first3=G. | last4=Nickels | first4=H. | title=Political and Cultural Representations of Muslims: Islam in the Plural | publisher=Brill | series=Muslim Minorities | year=2012 | isbn=978-90-04-23102-3 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nQ6OFETxDWAC&pg=PA137 | page=137}}</ref>
The term has also been used to describe alleged alliances of industrial union-focused leftists (''red''), ecologically-minded agrarians (''green''), and nationalists (''brown'').{{r|Strauss 2003}}{{r|The Buchanan Troll Project}}
It is often used in a broad sense to refer to [[Antisemitism|antisemitic]], [[anti-globalization]], [[Anti-Americanism|anti-American]], or [[Anti-Western sentiment|anti-Western]] views shared by disparate groups and movements.<ref name="Strauss 2003">{{cite magazine |last=Strauss |first=Mark |title=Antiglobalism's Jewish Problem |work=Foreign Policy |issue=139 |date=November 2003 |p=58-67 |issn=0015-7228 | doi=10.2307/3183738 |url=https://yaleglobal.yale.edu/content/antiglobalisms-jewish-problem }}<! -- more content here --></ref>{{r|Twersky 2000}}

== History ==

French essayist [[Alexandre del Valle]] wrote of "une alliance idéologique ... rouge-brun-vert" (''a red-green brown ... ideological alliance'') in an 22 April 2002 article in the newspaper ''[[Le Figaro]]'',<ref name="Del Valle & Knobel 2002">{{cite web |last1=Del Valle |first1=Alexandre |last2=Knobel |first2=Marc | title=Le Péril rouge en France ou la convergence des Totalitarismes |trans-title=The Red Peril in France: The convergence of totalitarianisms |work=Le Figaro | date=27 April 2002 <!-- 22 April 2002? --> | url=http://blog.alexandredelvalle.com/archives/12-Le-Peril-rouge-en-France-ou-la-convergence-des-Totalitarismes.html | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418232132/http://blog.alexandredelvalle.com/archives/12-Le-Peril-rouge-en-France-ou-la-convergence-des-Totalitarismes.html | archive-date=18 April 2012 | dead-url=yes | language=fr}} Also available from [https://harissa.com/D_forum/Judaisme/laconvergence.htm harissa.com].<!-- Unable to locate a copy from Le Figaro --></ref> and wrote "Rouges-Bruns-Verts, l'étrange alliance", in a January 2004 article in the magazine ''Politique Internationale''.<ref>A. Del Valle, [http://www.politiqueinternationale.com/revue/article.php?id_revue=24&id=522&content=synopsisin "Rouges-Bruns-Verts : L'étrange alliance"], Politique Internationale, no. 102 (january 2004), [https://www.alexandredelvalle.com/single-post/2004/12/06/The-Reds-The-Browns-and-the-Greens-or-The-Convergence-of-Totalitarianisms official translation]. Retrieved 7 May 2016.</ref>

Del Valle's conceptual rendering of Islamist ideological trends appears to be based, at least partially, on earlier writings in which he had charged the United States and western Europe with favouring the "war machine" of "armed Islamism" via its funding of the Afghani [[mujahideen]] during the [[Soviet–Afghan War]] during the presidency of [[Ronald Reagan]],<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Murawiec |first=Laurent |authorlink=Laurent Murawiec |title=The wacky world of French intellectuals |work=Middle East Quarterly |publisher=[[Middle East Forum]] |date=Spring 2000 |volume=8 |p=3-10 |url=https://www.meforum.org/articles/other/the-wacky-world-of-french-intellectuals}}</ref> which helped future enemies of the West.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}} In 2010, Del Valle published in Italy an essay entitled "{{lang|it|Rossi, Neri, Verdi: a convergenza degli Estremi opposti}}" (Red, Black, Green: The meeting of extreme opposites.)<ref>A. Del Valle, [http://www.loccidentale.it/articoli/82697/verdi-rossi-e-neri-chi-sono-i-nemici-delloccidente-e-perche-ci-odiano-cosi "Verdi, rossi e neri: chi sono i nemici dell'Occidente e perché ci odiano così], L'Occidentale (3 December 2009). Retrieved 7 May 2016.</ref>

The later popularity of the ''red-green-brown'' theory (and its various permutations) derives mainly from a speech given by [[Roger Cukierman]], president of the French Jewish organization [[Conseil Représentatif des Institutions juives de France|CRIF]], to a CRIF banquet on 25 January 2003, and given wide circulation by a 27/28 January 2003 article in ''[[Le Monde]]''. Cukierman used the French term "alliance brun-vert-rouge" to describe the antisemitic alignment supposedly shared by "an extreme right nostalgic for racial hierarchies" (symbolized by the color [[Sturmabteilung|brown]]), "an extreme left [which is] anti-globalist, anti-capitalist, anti-American [and] anti-Zionist" (red), and followers of [[José Bové]] (green).

In Great Britain in 2003, politician [[George Galloway]] announced that he was seeking "to unify the [[Socialism|red]], [[Green politics|green]], [[Opposition to the Iraq War|anti-war]], [[Islam in the United Kingdom|Muslim]] and other social constituencies radicalised by [[Iraq War|the war]]".<ref name="Peace 2013">{{cite news |title=All I'm asking, is for a little respect: Assessing the Performance of Britain's Most Successful Radical Left Party |last=Peace |first=Timothy |year=2013 |journal=Parliamentary Affairs |volume=66 |pages=405–424 |doi=10.1093/pa/gsr064}}</ref>{{rp|407}} Shortly thereafter, led by [[Salma Yaqoob]] and [[George Monbiot]], the [[Socialist Workers Party (UK)|Socialist Workers Party]] and the [[Muslim Association of Britain]] formed an alliance in the [[Respect Party]], under which Galloway ran for office. Respect initially tried to form an electoral pact with the [[Green Party of England and Wales]],{{r|Peace 2013|pp=407–408}}<ref>Matthew Tempest [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2004/feb/17/iraq.iraq1 "Monbiot quits Respect over threat to Greens"], ''The Guardian'', 17 February 2004</ref> but the Green Party refused to ally with Respect, saying that Respect did not align with their values of openness and democracy<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Cohen |first=Nick |date=2004 |title=Saddam's very own party |work=[[New Statesman]] |volume=13 |p=326-328 |url=https://www.newstatesman.com/node/195042}}</ref>{{r|Green Party 2004}} and had an under-developed [[political platform]] among other issues.<ref name="Green Party 2004">{{cite web|url=http://www.greenparty.org.uk/news/1008/l=7|title=Greens regret attack by Galloway/SWP "Respect" party|accessdate=23 April 2007|year=2004 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070413142818/http://www.greenparty.org.uk/news/1008/l=7 |archivedate = 13 April 2007}}</ref>

In the United States, a similar alliance of disparate groups occurred in opposition to the [[World Trade Organization]] in the [[alter-globalization movement]], which joined trade unions, [[neo-Luddite]] environmentalists, and [[paleoconservative]] [[Nationalism|nationalists]] like [[Pat Buchanan]] in common cause.<ref name="The Buchanan Troll Project">{{cite news |title=The Buchanan Troll Project |work=MetroWest Jewish News |volume=2 |issue=4 |date=13 January 2000 |location=Whippany, NJ, USA |url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/364868971 |url-access=subscription}}<!-- fully noted --></ref> Many were surprised by leftist [[Lenora Fulani]]'s support for Pat Buchanan, which has been viewed as an example of a red–green–brown alliance.<ref name="Twersky 2000">{{cite magazine |last=Twersky |first=David |date=27 January 2000 |title=Buchanan's voice bodes ill for israel |work=Jewish Exponent |volume=207 |number=4 |p=36 |location=Philadelphia, USA |publisher=Jewish Federation of Greater Philadelphia |url=https://search.proquest.com/docview/227249240}}</ref>

